photo.title: Shell Building San Francisco

description._content:
Facts

Winner of the 1994 San Francisco Architectural Heritage Award for excellence in architectural preservation for exterior restoration.
The building was built in exactly 300 days.
Office floors were designed with moving partitions.
Ornamental detail is carried inside the lobby and all elevator lobbies.
The top portion of the building's facade is decorated in sepia-glazed terra cotta with blue-green cast concrete spandrels and abstracted shell designs in reference to the building's owner.
Sanborn heights: 301 feet to floor 23, 352 feet to floor 27, 376 feet to top of floor 29.
Shell Oil Company, the building's namesake, ultimately vacated the building during the 1960s.
The two-story mezzanine lobby entrance features bronze doors, marble walls, and a sweeping 25-foot-high ceiling.

description._content: Leica M240, Summilux-M 35mm ASPH FLE The Shell Building is an office tower in the Financial District of San Francisco, California. The 28-story, 115.22 m (378.0 ft), building is located at 100 Bush Street, at Battery Street. It was designed by George W. Kelham and built in 1929, in the architectural style of Gothic Moderne, Moderne and Art Deco.[4] Shell Oil Company occupied the building until the 1960s. There are castings of shells that decorate the cornice on the upper levels as well as shell designs in the lobby floor and decorative grill at the front of the building.[5][6] Source: Wikipedia en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shell_Building_%28San_Francisco%29

description._content:
One Bush Plaza also known as the Crown-Zellerbach Building is an office building on Bush Street and Battery Street at Market Street in the Financial District of San Francisco, California. The 20-story, 94 m (308 ft) building was completed in 1959. (Skidmore, Owings & Merrill , architects)

The building was once the headquarters of the Crown-Zellerbach, a Fortune 500 forestry and paper products conglomerate acquired in 1986 by the James River Company, which in turn became a part of Georgia-Pacific in 2000. On December 23, 2005, Koch Industries finalized the $21 billion acquisition of Georgia-Pacific. Georgia-Pacific was removed from the NYSE (it had traded under the symbol GP) .

photo.title: In Pieces

description._content: This image is available as an art print from as little as US$10 at ameotoko.zenfolio.com/ I was shooting the archway of the Shell Building in downtown San Francisco when I noticed the fantastic reflection of the building in the glass skyscraper across the street. You probably think I was thinking "I'm creating the image of the juxtaposition of early 20th century art deco architecture with the soulessness of 21st century steel and glass." Actually, I was thinking "If someone opens the door behind me, they're going to knock me on my @$$."

photo.title: Crowning Achievements

description._content:
Two historic buildings in San Francisco.  On the left is the Crown-Zellerbach Building, now called One Bush Plaza. On the right is the Shell Building.  The double tower on the far right is the Mandarin Oriental Hotel.

Crown-Zellerbach, built in the 1950s, is a superb example of the International Style, a very clean and well-balanced modern structure.  The Shell Building, built in the 1930s, is classic Art Deco.

photo.title: Zellerbach Building from Shell Building

description._content:
San Francisco

1959 - Crown Zellerbach Building - One Bush Plaza - Construction began in 1957. Designed by a team led by Edward Basset of Skidmore, Owings and Merrill and originally built for the Crown Zellerbach Paper Company, it was the first significant office building to go up in San Francisco after the Great Depression. It was a stark contrast to traditional stone and masonry buildings that surrounded it. This is the circular Wells Fargo Bank, next to the tower, which is now occupied by "E-Trade" (at last check). During the late 1980s through 90s it was a "Sharper Image" retail store.
